In JavaScript, we can generate an infinite string of characters by using a generator function. Here is an example:

```javascript
function* characterGenerator() {
    let charCode = 0;
    while (true) {
        yield String.fromCharCode(charCode % 256);
        charCode++;
    }
}

const generator = characterGenerator();

// To generate a string of characters
function generateString(length) {
    let str = '';
    for (let i = 0; i < length; i++) {
        str += generator.next().value;
    }
    return str;
}

console.log(generateString(10));  // Output: "]~~~"
```

In this code, `characterGenerator` is a generator function that generates an infinite sequence of characters. It starts with the character whose Unicode code point is 0 (which is a non-printable control character), and then increments the character code at each iteration. The `generateString` function uses this generator to create a string of a given length.

Please note that this is an infinite sequence, so you can't actually create an infinite string with this code. However, you can generate as many characters as you want by increasing the length parameter.

Also, please note that the characters in the generated string are not meaningful or printable. This is because the Unicode code points are incremented without ever wrapping around to printable characters. If you want to generate a meaningful string, you'll need to restrict the range of the Unicode code points to those of printable characters.

