The module list in PEB is managed by the operating system and is updated automatically when modules are loaded or unloaded. Directly modifying this list can cause issues with the operating system's internal data structures and should not be done.

If you are trying to modify the module list for a legitimate reason, such as for debugging or testing, you should look for APIs provided by the operating system for interacting with the module list. For example, you might use the EnumProcessModules function to enumerate the modules loaded by a process, or the GetModuleHandle function to retrieve a handle to a module in the address space of the calling process.

Here's an example of how you might use GetModuleHandle to retrieve a module handle:

```cpp
HMODULE hModule = GetModuleHandle(NULL);
while (hModule!= NULL)
{
    // Process the module handle...

    hModule = GetModuleHandle(hModule);
}
```

In this example, GetModuleHandle is called repeatedly with the handle of the previously retrieved module until no more modules are found. Each call to GetModuleHandle retrieves the next module in the module list.

Please note that this is a simplified example and may not cover all aspects of module handling. The actual code will depend on your specific requirements and should be used with caution.

If you need to perform operations on each module in the module list, you should use the EnumProcessModules function instead. This function enumerates the modules loaded by a process and populates an array of module handles.

Here's an example of how you might use EnumProcessModules:

```cpp
HMODULE hMods[1024];
DWORD cbNeeded;

if (EnumProcessModules(GetCurrentProcess(), hMods, sizeof(hMods), &cbNeeded))
{
